{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"06f1b91f-8938-4640-813d-2dbc6d808ef0","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is only for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\nHere are the main tools for analyzing `.dmp` files from .NET apps:\n\n### `dotnet-dump analyze`\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump   # if not installed\ndotnet-dump analyze <your-file>.dmp\n```\nUseful SOS commands inside the session:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack of the crashing thread\n- `pe` (or `printexception`) — print the last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary (for OOM crashes)\n- `threads` — list all managed threads\n- `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` — inspect other threads\n\n### `lldb` (Linux/macOS)\n```bash\nlldb --core <your-file>.dmp\nplugin load libsosplugin.so\nclrstack\nprintexception\n```\n\n### Visual Studio / WinDbg (Windows)\nOpen the `.dmp` file directly; VS will offer \"Debug with Managed Only.\"\n\n---\n\n**Quick triage steps:**\n1. Run `dotnet-dump analyze your.dmp`\n2. Run `pe` to see if there's an unhandled exception\n3. Run `clrstack` to see what code was executing\n4. If it's an OOM, use `dumpheap -stat` to find large allocations\n\nWould you like me to run `dotnet-dump analyze` on your file? If so, provide the path to the `.dmp` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"92ae8bce-06ba-45ab-9d4e-acc1875ed57e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\". So I should not invoke that skill.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":492,"requestId":"AC02:12E269:141B584:1696B2F:6A067274"},"id":"4c06b487-98f1-41dc-b86